# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: archimedes-screw
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:archimedes-screw/agostino-ramelli] Ramelli was born in Ponte Tresa or Mesanzena, today in Switzerland.
[src:archimedes-screw/agostino-ramelli] During the Siege of La Rochelle (1572–1573), he successfully engineered a mine under a bastion and breached the fortification, making him popular with his commander, Henri d'Anjou, who later became King Henri III of France.
[src:archimedes-screw/agostino-ramelli] In 1588, Ramelli published *Le diverse et artificiose machine del Capitano Agostino Ramelli*, or *The various and ingenious machines of Captain Agostino Ramelli*.
[src:archimedes-screw/agostino-ramelli] The book contains 195 designs, over 100 of which are water-raising machines, such as water pumps or wells.
[src:archimedes-screw/agostino-ramelli] Other designs include bridges, mills, and a possible forerunner to the Wankel engine.
[src:archimedes-screw/agostino-ramelli] Some of his pump mechanisms feature early rotary and multi-piston concepts that conceptually resemble modern axial piston pumps (for example, those used today in car air conditioning compressors).
[src:archimedes-screw/agostino-ramelli] The bookwheel is one of the most famous designs from this book.
[src:archimedes-screw/agostino-ramelli] *Le diverse et artificiose machine* is still printed and sold.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] An **air compressor** is a machine that takes ambient air from the surroundings and discharges it at a higher pressure.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] It is an application of a gas compressor and a pneumatic device that converts mechanical power (from an electric motor, diesel or gasoline engine, etc.) into potential energy stored in compressed air, which has many uses.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] A common application is to compress air into a storage tank, for immediate or later use.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] When the delivery pressure reaches its set upper limit, the compressor is shut off, or the excess air is released through an overpressure valve.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] The compressed air is stored in the tank until it is needed.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] The pressure energy provided by the compressed air can be used for a variety of applications such as pneumatic tools as it is released.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] When tank pressure reaches its lower limit, the air compressor turns on again and re-pressurizes the tank.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] A compressor is different from a pump because it works on a gas, while pumps work on a liquid.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] There are numerous methods of air compression, divided into either positive-displacement or roto-dynamic types.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] Positive-displacement compressors work by forcing air through a chamber whose volume is decreased to compress the air.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] Once the pressure is greater than the pressure outside the discharge valve, a port or valve opens and air is discharged into the outlet system from the compression chamber.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] The capacities for both single-stage and two-stage compressors are generally specified in Standard Cubic feet per Minute (SCFM) or litres per minute and pounds per square Inch (PSI) or bar.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] To a lesser extent, some compressors are rated in actual cubic feet per minute (ACFM).
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] Still others are rated in cubic feet per minute (CFM).
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] Using CFM alone to rate a compressor is ambiguous because it represents a flow rate without a pressure reference. i.e.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] Single stage compressors usually fall into the fractional through 5 horsepower range.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] Two-stage compressors normally fall into the 5 through 30 horsepower range.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] Roto-dynamic air compressors include centrifugal compressors where Rotating vanes impart kinetic energy to a gas and stationary passages convert velocity into a rise in pressure, and axial compressors, where rotor blades impart the kinetic energy and stator blades convert it to a rise in pressure.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] Due to adiabatic heating, air compressors require some method of disposing of waste heat.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] Generally this is some form of air- or water-cooling, although some (particularly rotary type) compressors may be cooled by oil (that is then in turn air- or water-cooled).
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] The atmospheric changes are also considered during cooling of compressors.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] The type of cooling is determined by considering the factors such as inlet temperature, ambient temperature, power of the compressor and area of application.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] There is no single type of compressor that could be used for any application.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] Air compressors are also widely used in oil and gas, mining and drilling applications as the flushing medium, aerating muds in underbalanced drilling and in air pigging of pipelines.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] Most air compressors either are reciprocating piston type, rotary vane or rotary screw.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] Centrifugal compressors are common in very large applications, while rotary screw, scroll, and reciprocating air compressors are favoured for small and medium-sized applications.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] Air compressors are designed to utilize a variety of power sources.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] While direct drive gasoline or diesel-engines and electric motors are among the most popular, air compressors that utilize vehicle engines, power-take-off, or hydraulic ports are also commonly used in mobile applications.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] The power of a compressor is measured in HP (horsepower) and CFM (cubic feet per minute of intake air).
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] The volume of the pressure vessel and the stored pressure indicate the volume of compressed air (in reserve) available.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] Gasoline and diesel-powered compressors are widely used in remote areas with problematic access to electricity.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] They are noisy and require ventilation for exhaust gases, particularly if the compressed air is to be used for a breathing air supply.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] Electric-powered compressors are widely used in production, workshops and garages with permanent access to electricity.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] Common workshop/garage compressors are 110-120 Volt or 230-240 Volt.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] Compressor tank shapes are: "pancake", "twin tank", "horizontal", and "vertical".
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] Depending on a size and purpose compressors can be stationary or portable.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] To ensure all compressor types run efficiently with no leaks, it is necessary to perform routine maintenance.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] The cost of maintenance only accounts for 8% of the life cycle cost of owning an air compressor.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] According to CAGI air compressor performance verification data sheets, the higher the isentropic efficiency is, the better the energy saving is.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] The better air compressor isentropic efficiency has reached 95%.
[src:archimedes-screw/air-compressor] Approximately 70~80% of the air compressor's total lifetime cost is energy consumption, so using the high-efficiency air compressor is one of the energy-saving methods.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] As a political domain, it successively constituted a province of the Umayyad Caliphate, initiated by the Caliph al-Walid I (711–750); the Emirate of Córdoba (c.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Under the Caliphate of Córdoba, the city of Córdoba became one of the leading cultural and economic centres throughout the Mediterranean Basin, Europe, and the Islamic world.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Achievements that advanced Islamic and Western science came from al-Andalus, including major advances in trigonometry (Jabir ibn Aflah), astronomy (al-Zarqali), surgery (al-Zahrawi), pharmacology (Ibn Zuhr), and agronomy (Ibn Bassal and Abu'l-Khayr al-Ishbili).
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Al-Andalus became a conduit for cultural and scientific exchange between the Islamic and Christian worlds.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] For much of its history, al-Andalus existed in conflict with Christian kingdoms to the north.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] After the fall of the Umayyad Caliphate of Cordoba by 1031, al-Andalus was fragmented into *taifa* states and principalities, some of which (such as the Taifa of Toledo, the Taifa of Zaragoza, the Taifa of Seville and the Taifa of Badajoz) reached considerable territorial extent.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] After the Christian capture of Toledo in 1085, the Almoravid empire intervened and repelled attacks on the region, then brought al-Andalus under direct Almoravid rule.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] For the next century and a half, al-Andalus became a province of the Muslim empires of the Almoravids and their successors, the Almohads, both based in Marrakesh.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Ultimately, the northern Christian kingdoms overpowered the Muslim states to the south.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] In the 13th century, most of the south quickly fell under Christian rule, with Gharb al-Andalus, the Guadalquivir Valley and Eastern al-Andalus falling to Portuguese, Castilian, and Aragonese conquests.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] This left the Emirate of Granada as the remaining Muslim state on the Iberian Peninsula, which became a tributary state of the Crown of Castile, before surrendering in 1492 to the Catholic Monarchs.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The toponym *al-Andalus* is first attested by inscriptions on coins minted in 716 by the new Muslim government of Iberia.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] These coins, called *dinars*, were inscribed in both Latin and Arabic.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The etymology of the name *al-Andalus* has traditionally been derived from the name of the Vandals (*vándalos* in Spanish, *vândalos* in Portuguese).
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Since the 1980s, several alternative etymologies have challenged this tradition.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] In 1986, Joaquín Vallvé proposed that *al-Andalus* was a corruption of the name *Atlantis*.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Heinz Halm in 1989 derived the name from a Gothic term, **landahlauts*, and in 2002, Georg Bossong suggested its derivation from a pre-Roman substrate.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] During the caliphate of the Umayyad Caliph Al-Walid I, the commander Tariq ibn-Ziyad led an army of 7,000 that landed at Gibraltar on April 30, 711, ostensibly to intervene in a Visigothic civil war.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] After a decisive victory over King Roderic at the Battle of Guadalete on 19 July 711, Tariq, accompanied by his *mawla*, governor Musa ibn Nusayr of Ifriqiya, brought most of the Visigothic Kingdom under Muslim rule in a seven-year campaign.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] They crossed the Pyrenees and occupied Visigothic Septimania in southern France.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Most of the Iberian peninsula became part of the expanding Umayyad Empire, under the name of *al-Andalus*.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] It was organised as a province subordinate to Ifriqiya, so, for the first few decades, the governors of al-Andalus were appointed by the emir of Kairouan, rather than the Caliph in Damascus.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The regional capital was set at Córdoba, and the first influx of Muslim settlers was widely distributed.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Following the Muslim conquest of Spain, al-Andalus, then at its greatest extent, was divided into five administrative units, corresponding very roughly to: modern Andalusia; Castile and León; Navarre, Aragon, and Catalonia; Portugal and Galicia; and the Languedoc-Roussillon area of Occitania.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The small army Tariq led in the initial conquest consisted mostly of Berbers, while Musa's largely Arab force of over 12,000 soldiers was accompanied by a group of *mawālī* (Arabic, موالي), that is, non-Arab Muslims, who were clients of the Arabs.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The Berber soldiers accompanying Tariq were garrisoned in the centre and the north of the peninsula, as well as in the Pyrenees, while the Berber colonists who followed settled in all parts of the country – north, east, south and west.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Visigothic lords who agreed to recognise Muslim suzerainty were allowed to retain their fiefs (notably, in Murcia, Galicia, and the Ebro valley).
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Resistant Visigoths took refuge in the Cantabrian highlands, where they carved out a rump state, the Kingdom of Asturias.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] In the 720s, the al-Andalus governors launched several *sa'ifa* raids into Aquitaine but were decisively defeated by Duke Odo the Great of Aquitaine at the Battle of Toulouse (721).
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] At the Battle of Poitiers in 732, the al-Andalus raiding army was defeated by Charles Martel and Al Ghafiqi was killed.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] In 734, the Andalusi launched raids to the east, capturing Avignon and Arles, and overran much of Provence.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] In 737, they travelled up the Rhône valley, reaching as far north as Burgundy.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Charles Martel of the Franks, with the assistance of Liutprand of the Lombards, invaded Burgundy and Provence and expelled the raiders by 739.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] In 740, a Berber Revolt erupted in the Maghreb (North Africa).
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] To put down the rebellion, the Umayyad Caliph Hisham dispatched a large Arab army, composed of regiments (*Junds*) from Bilad Ash-Sham, to North Africa.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] This Umayyad army was defeated by the Berber rebels at the Battle of Bagdoura (in Morocco).
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Heartened by the victories of their North African brethren, the Berbers of al-Andalus quickly raised their own revolt.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Berber garrisons in the north of the Iberian Peninsula mutinied, deposed their Arab commanders, and organised a large rebel army to march against the strongholds of Toledo, Córdoba, and Algeciras.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] In 741, Balj bin Bishr led a detachment of some 10,000 Arab troops across the straits.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The Arab governor of al-Andalus, joined by this force, was victorious over the Berber rebels in a series of battles in 742.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] A dispute erupted between the Syrian commanders and the Andalusi, the so-called "original Arabs" of the earlier contingents.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The Syrians defeated them at the hard-fought Battle of Aqua Portora in August 742 but were too few to impose themselves on the province.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The Egypt jund was divided between Beja (Alentejo) in the west and Tudmir (Murcia) in the east.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The arrival of the Syrians substantially increased the Arab element in the Iberian peninsula and helped strengthen the Muslim hold on the south.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] However, at the same time, unwilling to be governed, the Syrian *junds* carried on an existence of autonomous feudal anarchy, severely destabilising the authority of the governor of al-Andalus.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] A second significant consequence of the revolt was the expansion of the Kingdom of the Asturias, hitherto confined to enclaves in the Cantabrian highlands.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] After the rebellious Berber garrisons evacuated the northern frontier fortresses, the Christian king Alfonso I of Asturias set about immediately seizing the empty forts for himself, quickly adding the northwestern provinces of Galicia and León to his fledgling kingdom.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The Asturians evacuated the Christian populations from the towns and villages of the Galician-Leonese lowlands, creating an empty buffer zone in the Douro River valley (the "Desert of the Duero").
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] This newly emptied frontier remained roughly in place for the next few centuries as the boundary between the Christian north and the Islamic south.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] On the Muslim side of the frontier, al-Andalus had three large march territories (*thaghr*, pl.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] These disturbances and disorder also allowed the Franks, now under the leadership of Pepin the Short, to invade the strategic strip of Septimania in 752, hoping to deprive al-Andalus of an easy launching pad for raids into Francia.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] After a lengthy siege, the last Arab stronghold, the citadel of Narbonne, finally fell to the Franks in 759.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Al-Andalus was sealed off at the Pyrenees.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The third consequence of the Berber revolt was the collapse of the authority of the Damascus Caliphate over the western provinces.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] With the Umayyad Caliphs distracted by the challenge of the Abbasids in the east, the western provinces of the Maghreb and al-Andalus spun out of their control.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] From around 745, the Fihrids, an illustrious local Arab clan descended from Oqba ibn Nafi al-Fihri, seized power in the western provinces and ruled them almost as a private family empire of their own – Abd al-Rahman ibn Habib al-Fihri in Ifriqiya and Yūsuf al-Fihri in al-Andalus.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The Fihrids welcomed the fall of the Umayyads in the east, in 750, and sought to reach an understanding with the Abbasids, hoping they might be allowed to continue their autonomous existence.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] But when the Abbasids rejected the offer and demanded submission, the Fihrids declared independence and, probably out of spite, invited the deposed remnants of the Umayyad clan to take refuge in their dominions.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] It was a fateful decision that they soon regretted, for the Umayyads, the sons and grandsons of caliphs, had a more legitimate claim to rule than the Fihrids themselves.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Rebellious-minded local lords, disenchanted with the autocratic rule of the Fihrids, conspired with the arriving Umayyad exiles.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] In 755, the exiled Umayyad prince Abd al-Rahman I (also called *al-Dākhil*, the 'Immigrant') arrived on the coast of Spain.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] He had fled the Abbasids, who had overthrown the Umayyads in Damascus and were slaughtering members of that family, and then he spent four years in exile in North Africa, assessing the political situation in al-Andalus across the Straits of Gibraltar, before he landed at Almuñécar.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] News of his arrival spread across al-Andalus, and when word reached its governor, Yūsuf al-Fihri, he was not pleased.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] During this time, Abd al-Rahman and his supporters quickly conquered Málaga and then Seville, finally besieging the capital of al-Andalus, Córdoba.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Abd al-Rahman's army was exhausted after their conquest, meanwhile Governor Yūsuf al-Fihri had returned from quashing another rebellion with his army.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The siege of Córdoba began, and noticing the starving state of Abd al-Rahman's army, al-Fihri began throwing lavish feasts every day as the siege went on, to tempt Abd al Rahman's supporters to defect to his side.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] However, Abd al-Rahman persisted, even rejecting a truce that would have allowed Abd al-Rahman to marry al-Fihri's daughter.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] After decisively defeating Yūsuf al-Fihri's army, Abd al-Rahman was able to conquer Córdoba, where he proclaimed himself emir in 756.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The rest of al-Andalus was easily conquered, and Abd al-Rahman soon had control of all of al-Andalus.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] By far the most important of these invasions was the attempted reconquest by the Abbasid Caliphate.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] In 763 Caliph Al-Mansur of the Abbasids installed al-Ala ibn-Mugith as governor of Africa (whose title gave him dominion over the province of al-Andalus).
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] He planned to invade and destroy the Emirate of Córdoba, so in response Abd al Rahman fortified himself within the fortress of Carmona with a tenth as many soldiers as al-Ala ibn-Mugith.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] After a long siege, it appeared that Abd al Rahman would be defeated, but in a last stand Abd al Rahman with his outnumbered forces opened the gates of the fortress and charged at the resting Abbasid army, and decisively defeated them.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Abd al Rahman I died in 788 after a lengthy and prosperous reign.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] He was succeeded by his son, Hisham I, who secured power by exiling his brother who had tried to rebel against him.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Hisham enjoyed a stable reign of eight years and was succeeded by his son Al-Hakam I.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The next few decades were relatively uneventful, with only occasional minor rebellions, and saw the rise of the emirate.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] In 822 Al Hakam died and was succeeded by Abd al-Rahman II, the first great emir of Córdoba.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] He rose to power with no opposition and sought to reform the emirate.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] He quickly reorganised the bureaucracy to be more efficient and built many mosques across the emirate.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] During his reign science and art flourished, as many scholars fled the Abbasid caliphate due to the disastrous Fourth Fitna.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The scholar Abbas ibn Firnas made an attempt to fly, though accounts vary on his success.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] In 852 Abd al Rahman II died, leaving behind him a powerful and well-established state that had become one of the most powerful in the Mediterranean.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Abd al Rahman was succeeded by Muhammad I of Córdoba, who according to legend had to wear women's clothing to sneak into the imperial palace and be crowned, since he was not the heir apparent.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] His reign marked a decline in the emirate, which was ended by Abd al-Rahman III.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] His reign was marked by multiple rebellions, which were dealt with poorly and weakened the emirate, most disastrously following the rebellion of Umar ibn Hafsun.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] When Muhammad died, he was succeeded by emir Abdullah ibn Muhammad al-Umawi whose power barely reached outside of the city of Córdoba.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] As Ibn Hafsun ravaged the south, Abdullah did almost nothing, and slowly became more and more isolated, barely speaking to anyone.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Abdullah purged his administration of his brothers, which lessened the bureaucracy's loyalty towards him.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Around this time several local Arab lords began to revolt, including one Kurayb ibn Khaldun, who was able to conquer Seville.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Some loyalists tried to quell the rebellion, but without proper material support, their efforts were in vain.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] He declared that the next emir would be his grandson Abd al-Rahman III, ignoring the claims of his four living children.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Abdullah died in 912, and the throne passed to Abd al Rahman III.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Through force of arms and diplomacy, he put down the rebellions that had disrupted his grandfather's reign, obliterating Ibn Hafsun and hunting down his sons.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] After this he led several sieges against the Christians, sacking the city of Pamplona, and restoring some prestige to the emirate.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Meanwhile, across the sea the Fatimids had risen up in force, ousted the Abbasid government in North Africa, and declared themselves a caliphate.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Inspired by this action, Abd al Rahman joined the rebellion and declared himself caliph in 929.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] For nearly 100 years under the Córdoban Umayyad period, from the 9th century to the 10th, al-Andalus also extended its presence from Fraxinetum into the Alps with a series of organised raids.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The period of the Caliphate is seen as the golden age of al-Andalus.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Córdoba under the Caliphate, with a population of more than half a million, eventually overtook Constantinople as the largest and most prosperous city in the world.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Al-Andalus became a centre for the arts, medicine, science, music, literature and philosophy.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The work of its most important philosophers and scientists, such as Abulcasis and Averroes, had a major influence on the intellectual life of medieval Europe.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Muslims and non-Muslims often came from abroad to study at the libraries and universities of al-Andalus, and after the reconquest of Toledo, several translation institutions such as the Toledo School of Translators were established for translating books and texts from Arabic into Latin.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The most noted figures in this being Gerard of Cremona and Michael Scot, who took these works to Italy.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The transmission of ideas significantly affected the formation of the European Renaissance.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The Caliphate of Córdoba also had extensive trade with other parts of the Mediterranean, including Christian parts.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Trade goods included luxury items (silk, ceramics, gold), essential foodstuffs (grain, olive oil, wine), and containers (such as ceramics for storing perishables).
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] In the tenth century, Amalfitans were already trading Fatimid and Byzantine silks in Córdoba.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Later references to Amalfitan merchants were sometimes used to emphasise the previous golden age of Córdoba.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Fatimid Egypt was a supplier of many luxury goods, including elephant tusks, and raw or carved crystals.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The Fatimids were traditionally thought to be the only supplier of such goods, and control over these trade routes would be a cause for conflict between the Umayyads and Fatimids.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The Caliphate of Córdoba effectively collapsed during a ruinous civil war between 1009 and 1013, although it was not finally abolished until 1031 when *al-Andalus* broke up into a number of mostly independent mini-states and principalities called *taifas*.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] In 1013, invading Berbers sacked Córdoba, massacring its inhabitants, pillaging the city, and burning the palace complex to the ground.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The largest of the taifas to emerge were Badajoz (*Batalyaws*), Toledo (*Ṭulayṭulah*), Zaragoza (*Saraqusta*), and Granada (*Ġarnāṭah*).
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] During the eleventh century several centres of power existed among the taifas, and the political situation shifted rapidly.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The taifas were vulnerable and divided but had immense wealth.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] During its prominence the Taifa of Seville produced technically complex lusterware and exerted significant influence on ceramic production across al-Andalus.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] In the 1080s, the *taifa* kingdoms began to face an existential threat from the Christian kingdoms to the north, as Alfonso VI of Castile escalated attacks against them.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] In 1083, he led a punitive expedition against Seville that reached all the way to Tarifa at the southern tip of al-Andalus.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] In 1085, he annexed Toledo, a turning point which galvanised the remaining *taifa* leaders into seeking outside help.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] After the fall of Toledo, most of the major *taifa* rulers agreed to request the intervention of the Almoravids, a Berber empire based in Marrakesh that had conquered much of northwest Africa.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The Almoravid leader, Yusuf Ibn Tashfin, led several campaigns into al-Andalus, initially in defence of the *taifa* kingdoms.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] At the Battle of Sagrajas (or Battle of Zallaqa in Arabic), a Muslim army led by the Almoravids soundly defeated Alfonso VI.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] By 1090, however, Yusuf ibn Tashfin was disillusioned with the disunity of the *taifa* leaders and he returned on a campaign to conquer al-Andalus instead.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Most of the *taifas*, except for Zaragoza, were annexed by 1094.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Valencia, which had come under the control of El Cid at the end of its taifa period, was eventually occupied in 1102, after El Cid's death.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The rise and fall of the Almoravids is sometimes seen as an expression of Ibn Khaldun's asabiyyah paradigm.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] By 1147, the Almoravids were overthrown in North Africa by the Almohads, another Berber dynasty, under the leadership of Abd al-Mu'min.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] As Almoravid rule collapsed, another brief period of *taifa* kingdoms followed in al-Andalus, during which the Christian kingdoms expanded southward again.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] From 1146 onward, the Almohads intervened and took control of al-Andalus.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] One of Abd al-Mu'min's successors, Ya'qub al-Mansur, won a major victory over the Castilian Alfonso VIII at the Battle of Alarcos in 1195.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] In 1212, a coalition of Christian kings under the leadership of Alfonso VIII defeated the Almohads at the Battle of Las Navas de Tolosa.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Almohad rule was diminished in prestige and in 1228 the Almohad caliph al-Ma'mun withdrew from al-Andalus altogether.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] In this political vacuum, a new wave of *taifa* kingdoms emerged, which were progressively conquered by Portugal, Castile, and Aragon.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Córdoba was conquered in 1236 and Seville was conquered in 1248.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Some Muslim city-states, such as Murcia and Niebla, survived as vassal kingdoms of Castile until the 1260s.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Only the region of Granada remained unconquered.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] From the mid 13th to the late 15th century, the only remaining domain of al-Andalus was the Emirate of Granada, the last Muslim stronghold in the Iberian Peninsula.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The emirate was established by Muhammad ibn al-Ahmar in 1230 and was ruled by the Nasrid dynasty, the longest reigning dynasty in the history of al-Andalus.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Although surrounded by Castilian lands, the emirate was wealthy through being tightly integrated in Mediterranean trade networks and enjoyed a period of considerable cultural and economic prosperity.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Despite internal conflicts, the Nasrids of Granada were able to survive in part by playing the Christian kingdoms of the north against each other, while at other times soliciting aid from the Marinids, a new Berber dynasty ruling in North Africa from their capital in Fez.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] For much of its existence, Granada paid tribute to the Castilian kings.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Along with this political status, its favourable geographic location, with the Sierra Nevada as a natural barrier, helped to prolong Nasrid rule.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Granada also accommodated a large number of Muslim refugees fleeing the *Reconquista* or expelled from Christian-controlled territories, which grew the city and the emirate's population.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The city even became one of the largest in Europe throughout the 15th century in terms of population.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The most visible legacy of the Nasrids is the Alhambra, their fortified palace complex, partly preserved today.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The independent Nasrid kingdom was also a trade hub between the Atlantic and Mediterranean, and was frequented especially by Genoese merchants.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The Marinids intervened in the south of the Iberian Peninsula multiple times up until their defeat at the Battle of Río Salado in 1340.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] After this, they ceased to play a major role.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The subsequent internal turmoil within Castile, however, helped Nasrid Granada to enjoy a period of relative external peace and internal prosperity until the end of the 14th century, under the reigns of Yusuf I (r.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Important cultural figures, such as Ibn al-Khatib, Ibn Zamrak, and Ibn Khaldun all served in the Nasrid court during this period.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] In 1468, Isabella, the only child of Henry IV of Castile, married Ferdinand, the son of John II of Aragon, and by 1479 they were rulers of a united Castile and Aragon.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] This development meant that Granada could no longer exploit divisions between the two kingdoms and the new royal couple, also known as the Catholic Monarchs, were united in their intention to conquer it.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The final war to conquer Granada began in earnest in 1482.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Year by year, the Christian advance captured new cities and fortresses until the last Nasrid ruler, Muhammad XI (known as Boabdil to the Christians), formally surrendered Granada to the Catholic Monarchs on January 2, 1492.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] By this time Muslims in Castile numbered half a million.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] After the fall, "100,000 had died or been enslaved, 200,000 emigrated, and 200,000 remained as the residual population.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] From 1492 to 1493, tens of thousands of expulsed Muslims and Jews from al-Andalus were rescued when the Ottomans under orders of Sultan Bayezid II sent ships.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Thousands of Jews were transported to Ottoman lands, and many settled in North Africa.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Mass forced conversions of Muslims in 1499 led to a revolt that spread to Alpujarras and the mountains of Ronda; after this uprising the capitulations were revoked.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] In 1502 the Catholic Monarchs decreed the forced conversion of all Muslims living under the rule of the Crown of Castile, although in the kingdoms of Aragon and Valencia (both now part of Spain) the open practice of Islam was allowed until 1526.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Descendants of the Muslims were subject to expulsions from Spain between 1609 and 1614 (see Expulsion of the Moriscos).
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The last mass prosecution against Moriscos for crypto-Islamic practices occurred in Granada in 1727, with most of those convicted receiving relatively light sentences.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The Morisco community including these final convicts kept their identity alive at least through the late eighteenth century.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] There was much scientific activity in al-Andalus, especially in the fields of medicine, astronomy, mathematics, and agronomy.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] At the same time, Andalusi scholars were also highly active in philosophy (see below), especially in the field of logic.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The earliest evidence of such activities in al-Andalus dates to the reign of Abd ar-Rahman II (r.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] 822–852), when developments were spurred by exposure to older works translated from, Greek, Persian and other languages.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Scientific studies continued to be pursued in the following centuries, though certain fields and subjects thrived more depending on the period.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Scholars often worked in many different and overlapping subjects, so it is difficult to place those discussed here into a single scientific field each.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] There were many notable surgeons, physicians, and medical scholars from al-Andalus including Ibn al-Baytar (d.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] 1248), Abu al-Qasim al-Zahrawi (Albucasis; d.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] 1360), Abu Marwan 'Abd al-Malik ibn Habib (d.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] 853), and Abu Marwan ibn Zuhr (Avenzoar; d.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] This encyclopaedia is also significant for its inclusion of al-Zahrawi's personal experiences as a surgeon, which provided important case studies for aspiring surgeons.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] This distinguishes it from other strictly factual medical works of the time, most notably Ibn Sina's *Canon of Medicine*.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Ibn Habib's work is significant because it is one of the oldest known writings in the field of prophetic medicine, which uses hadiths to create Islamic-based medicinal guidelines.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] His book is also significant because it uses principles of Galenic medicine, such as humorism and the theory of four temperaments, as the basis of its medical recommendations.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The ibn Zuhr family played a very important role in the production of Andalusi medical knowledge, as they produced five generations of medical experts, particularly in the fields of dietary sciences and medicaments.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] In *Kitab al-Taysir* he provides one of the earliest clinical descriptions of the scabies mite.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The Maristan of Granada was founded in 1367 by the Nasrid ruler Muhammad V of Granada and stands as one of the clearest examples of institutional medicine in late al-Andalus.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Established as a charitable hospital in the Islamic tradition, it provided care for the sick, including those suffering from mental illness, and was funded through religious endowment.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Contemporary sources describe it as a purpose-built structure organised around a central courtyard with water features, reflecting both hygienic and therapeutic concerns.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The maristan illustrates the integration of medical practice, urban planning, and social welfare in Nasrid Granada, continuing the broader Andalusi engagement with the classical medical heritage of figures such as Ibn Sina while adapting it to local needs.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The maristam has reopened in recent years as a museum for visitors.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Three of the most notable Andalusi astronomers were Ibn Tufail (d.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] 1198), and Nur ad-Din al-Bitruji (Alpetragius; d.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] All lived around the same time and focused their astronomical works on critiquing and revising Ptolemaic astronomy and the problem of the equant in his astronomical model.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Instead, they accepted Aristotle's model and promoted the theory of homocentric spheres.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Al-Bitruji is believed to have studied under Ibn Tufail and Bitruji's *Book on Cosmology* (*Kitab fi al-hay'a*) built on Ibn Tufail's work, as well as that of Ibn Rushd, Ibn Bajja, and Maimonides.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] The book's goal was "to overcome the physical difficulties inherent in the geometrical models of Ptolemy's *Almagest* and to describe the cosmos in agreement with Aristotelian or Neoplatonic physics," which it succeeded in doing to an extent.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Bitruji's book set a precedent of criticising the *Almagest* in future works in the field of astronomy.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Although Ibn Rushd originally trained and practiced as a jurist, he was exposed to astronomy—possibly through Ibn Tufail—and became a renowned scientist in the field.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] His most popular work was his *Summary of the Almagest*, but he also published shorter works discussing Aristotle's planetary theories.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Ibn Rushd published writings on philosophy, theology, and medicine throughout his life too, including commentaries on the works of Ibn Sina.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] In addition to writing the important *Book of the Medicine of the Arabs*, Ibn Habib also wrote the *Book on Stars* (*Kirab fi l-nujim*).
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] This book included important "teachings on the lunar mansions, the signs of the zodiac, [and] the division of the seasons." In these teachings, Ibn-Habib calculated the phases of the moon and dates of the annual solstices and equinoxes with relative accuracy.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Another important astronomer from al-Andalus was Maslama al-Majriti (d.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] 1007), who played a role in translating and writing about Ptolemy's *Planisphaerium* and *Almagest*.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] He built on the work of older astronomers, like Muhammad ibn Musa al-Khwarizmi, whose astronomical tables he wrote a discussion on and subsequently improved.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] 1087) had many influential astronomical successes, as shown by Copernicus's recognition of him in his *On the Revolutions of the Heavenly Spheres* five centuries later.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Along with other astronomers, he undertook extensive work to edit the Toledan Zij astronomical tables.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] He also accurately calculated the motion of the solar apogee to be 12.04 seconds per year, which is relatively close to today's calculation of 11.8 seconds per year.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Other important scientific advances in al-Andalus occurred in the field of agronomy.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] These advances were in part facilitated by technological innovations in irrigation systems.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] State organised, large-scale irrigation projects provided water to city baths, mosques, gardens, residential homes, and governing palaces, such as the al-Hambra and its gardens in Granada.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Collective, peasant-built irrigation infrastructure also played an important role, especially in agriculture.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Many of these irrigation techniques, especially those utilised by peasants, were brought to al-Andalus by migrating Berber and Arab tribes.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Although some irrigation projects built on existing Roman infrastructure, most of al-Andalus's irrigation systems were new projects built separate from old Roman aqueducts.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] However, there is some debate about this among scholars.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] One notable agriculturalist was Ibn al-'Awwam, who wrote the *Book of Agriculture*.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] This book contains 34 chapters about various aspects of agriculture and animal husbandry, including discussions of over 580 different types of plants and how to treat plant diseases.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p01] Other agronomic innovations in al-Andalus include the cultivation of the pomegranate from Syria, which has since become the namesake and ubiquitous symbol of the city of Granada, as well as the first attempt to create a botanical garden near Córdoba by 'Abd al-Rahman I.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The society of al-Andalus was made up of three main religious groups: Muslims, Christians, and Jews.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The Muslims, although united on the religious level, had several ethnic divisions, the main being the distinction between the Arabs and the Berbers.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The Arab elite regarded non-Arab Muslims as second-class citizens; and they were particularly scornful of the Berbers.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The ethnic structure of al-Andalus consisted of Arabs at the top of the social scale followed by, in descending order, Berbers, Muladies, Mozarabes, and Jews.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Each of these communities inhabited distinct neighbourhoods in the cities.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] In the 10th century a massive conversion of Christians took place, and *muladies* formed the majority of Muslims.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Thomas Glick claims that Muladies, together with other Muslims, comprised eighty per cent of the population of al-Andalus by 1100.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Mozarabs were Christians who had long lived under Muslim and Arab rule, adopting many Arab customs, art and architecture, and words, while still maintaining their Christian and Latin rituals and their own Romance languages.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The Jewish population worked mainly as tax collectors, in trade, or as doctors or ambassadors.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] At the end of the 15th century there were about 50,000 Jews in Granada and roughly 100,000 in the whole of Islamic Iberia, which had been reduced to the territory of the Emirate of Granada.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Non-Muslims were given the status of *ahl al-dhimma* (people under protection), with adult men paying a "Jizya" tax equal to one dinar per year with exemptions for the elderly and the disabled.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Those who were neither Christians nor Jews, such as pagans, were given the status of *Majus*.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The treatment of non-Muslims in the Caliphate has been a subject of considerable debate among scholars and commentators, especially those interested in drawing parallels to the co-existence of Muslims and non-Muslims in the modern world.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Jews constituted more than five per cent of the population.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Al-Andalus was a key centre of Jewish life during the early Middle Ages, produced important scholars and was one of the most stable and wealthy Jewish communities.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Southern Iberia became an asylum for the oppressed Jews of other countries.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Under the Almoravids and the Almohads, there may have been intermittent persecution of Jews, but sources are extremely scarce and do not give a clear picture though the situation appears to have deteriorated after 1160.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Muslim pogroms against Jews in al-Andalus occurred in Córdoba (1011) and in Granada (1066).
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] However, massacres of *dhimmis* are believed to be rare in Islamic history.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The Almohads, who had taken control of the Almoravids' Maghribi and Andalusi territories by 1147, far surpassed the Almoravides in fundamentalist outlook, and treated the non-Muslims harshly.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Faced with the choice of either death or conversion, many Jews and Christians emigrated.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Some, such as the family of Maimonides, fled east to more tolerant Muslim lands.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Many ethnicities and religions co-existed in al-Andalus, each of which contributed to its intellectual prosperity.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Literacy in Islamic Iberia was far more widespread than in many other nations in the West of the time.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Though the number of the early inhabitants of al-Andalus after the 7th-century conquest was small, many native Iberian inhabitants converted to Islam, known as *Muwalladun* in Arabic or *Muladíes* in Spanish.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] By 1000, according to Ronald Segal, some 5,000,000 of Iberia's 7,000,000 inhabitants, most of them descended from indigenous Iberian converts, were Muslim.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] There were also Sub-Saharan Africans who had been absorbed into al-Andalus to be used as soldiers and slaves.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The Berber and the sub-Saharan African soldiers were known as "tangerines" because they were imported through the Mediterranean coastal city of Tangier.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] In the 11th century, the Hindu-Arabic numeral system (base 10) had reached Europe via al-Andalus through Spanish Muslims, together with knowledge of astronomy and instruments like the astrolabe, which was first imported by Gerbert of Aurillac.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] For that reason, the numerals came to be known in Europe as Arabic numerals despite their origins in India.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] From the earliest days, the Umayyads wanted to be seen as intellectual rivals to the Abbasids and for Córdoba to have libraries and educational institutions to that of their rival, Baghdad.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Although there was a clear rivalry between the two powers, there was freedom to travel between the two caliphates, which helped spread new ideas and innovations over time.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Multilingual households were an attested phenomenon.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Initially, most of the population spoke Romance dialects.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The dialects of Iberian Romance that were spoken in al-Andalus are collectively referred to as Andalusi Romance or Mozarabic.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] What is hypothesised about these dialects is based on sparse evidence, including Romance topographical and personal names and the *kharjas* of some **muwaššaḥ** poetry.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Arabic arrived with the Umayyad conquest of Hispania in 711 and spread gradually over the following centuries, primarily through conversion to Islam.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The vernacular varieties of Arabic spoken in al-Andalus, referred to as Andalusi Arabic, were Maghrebi Arabic dialects influenced by their contact with Romance, just as Arabic influenced Spanish.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] By about 1260, following the Almohad period, most Christians had migrated to the north and Muslim territories in Iberia were reduced to the Emirate of Granada, in which more than 90% of the population had converted to Islam and Arabic-Romance bilingualism seems to have largely disappeared.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The literary traditions of Hebrew—which was used for prayer and ceremonial writings, but not for oral communication—experienced a revolution through contact with Arabic and its literary traditions.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Consuelo López Morillas writes that Jews in al-Andalus "wrote Hebrew poetry using Arabic prosodic models and adopted nearly the entire range of Arabic poetic genres and stylistic devices in Hebrew," looking to Biblical Hebrew as a source for literary expression as Muslims looked to Quranic Arabic.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Berber languages, referred to in contemporary sources as *al-lisān al-gharbī* (اللسان الغربي, Arabic for 'the western tongue'), were especially present in periods of Berber rule, particularly under the Almoravids and Almohads.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Under Almohad rule, it was compulsory to deliver the *khuṭba* (sermon) at Friday prayer in Arabic and *al-lisān al-gharbī*.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] In al-Andalus, there are 11,831 known scholars who were active and 13,730 known works that were written or transmitted from the eighth to fifteenth centuries.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Of these scholars, those who are well known and remembered in the West, such as Ibn Rushd, Ibn Hazm, or Ibn Arabi, are not necessarily the same scholars that are remembered in Islamic culture, such as Abū ʿUmar b. ʿAbd al-Barr, Abū l-Walīd al-Bājī, Ibn ʿAtịyya, Ibn al-ʿArīf, or Abū Isḥāq aš-Šāṭibī.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Poetry was considered the prime literary genre in Arabic.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Traditional forms of Arabic poetry from the Mashriq, or Muslim East, especially the monometer, monorhyme *qaṣīda* and the prosimetric *maqāma*, were adopted in al-Andalus.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The major Andalusi innovation in poetry was the 'rhyme revolution' embodied in the 10th-11th century strophic song form called the *muwaššaḥ* ('girdled'; pl.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The *muwaššaḥ* features a complex rhyme scheme usually containing five *aghsān* ('branches'; sing.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] *ghusn*), with uniform rhyme within each strophe, interspersed with *asmāṭ* ('threads for stringing pearls'; sing.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] *simṭ*) with common rhyme throughout the song, as well as a terminal *kharja*, the song's final *simṭ*, which could be in a different language.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Andalusi *zajal* was strophic poetry in Andalusi vernacular Arabic, usually associated with Ibn Quzman.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Andalusi strophic poetry had an impact on poetic expression in Western Europe, especially the Old Occitan/Provençal lyric of the troubadours, and in the wider Muslim world.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The music of al-Andalus is part of an influential musical tradition.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Ziryab, a poet and musician, who came from the Abbasid Caliphate and arrived in Córdoba in 822, played a role in Andalusi music as well as other aspects of Andalusi culture.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Poetic forms such as the *muwashshah* and its *kharja*, the *nawba*, and the *zajal* are prominent in Andalusi music.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The historian Said al-Andalus wrote that Caliph Abd-ar-Rahman III had collected libraries of books and granted patronage to scholars of medicine and "ancient sciences".
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Later, *al-Mustansir* (Al-Hakam II) went yet further, building a university and libraries in Córdoba.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Córdoba became one of the world's leading centres of medicine and philosophical debate.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] When Al-Hakam's son Hisham II took over, real power was ceded to the *hajib*, al-Mansur Ibn Abi Aamir.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Al-Mansur was a distinctly religious man and disapproved of the sciences of astronomy, logic, and especially of astrology, so much so that many books on these subjects, which had been preserved and collected at great expense by Al-Hakam II, were burned publicly.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] With Al-Mansur's death in 1002, interest in philosophy revived.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Numerous scholars emerged, including Abu Uthman Ibn Fathun, whose masterwork was the philosophical treatise "Tree of Wisdom".
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Maslamah Ibn Ahmad al-Majriti (died 1008) was an outstanding scholar in astronomy and astrology; he was an intrepid traveller who journeyed all over the Islamic world and beyond and kept in touch with the Brethren of Purity.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] He is said to have brought the 51 "Epistles of the Brethren of Purity" to *al-Andalus* and added the compendium to this work, although it is quite possible that it was added later by another scholar with the name al-Majriti.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Another book attributed to al-Majriti is the *Ghayat al-Hakim*, "The Aim of the Sage", which explored a synthesis of Platonism with Hermetic philosophy.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Its use of incantations led the book to be widely dismissed in later years, although the Sufi communities continued to study it.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] A prominent follower of al-Majriti was the philosopher and geometer Abu al-Hakam al-Kirmani who was followed, in turn, by Abu Bakr Ibn al-Sayigh, usually known in the Arab world as Ibn Bajjah, "Avempace".
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The al-Andalus philosopher Averroes (1126–1198) was the founder of the Averroism school of philosophy, and his works and commentaries influenced medieval thought in Western Europe.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Another influential al-Andalus philosopher was Ibn Tufail.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] As Jewish thought in Babylonia declined, the tolerance of *al-Andalus* made it the new centre of Jewish intellectual endeavours.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Poets and commentators like Judah Halevi (1086–1145) and Dunash ben Labrat (920–990) contributed to the cultural life of *al-Andalus*, but the area was even more important to the development of Jewish philosophy.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] In al-Andalus, Jews played a significant role in the medical sphere and achieved prominence as physicians.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Hasdai ibn Shaprut, a Jewish court official and physician in 10th-century Córdoba, was involved in the Arabic translation of Dioscorides' *Materia Medica*, collaborating with both Christian and Muslim scholars.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] In 11th-century Zaragoza, Jonah ibn Janah authored a pharmacological treatise that provided multilingual drug names and detailed discussions of weights and measures used in medicine.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] His contemporary, Jonah ibn Biklārish, compiled a medical dictionary for Zaragoza's rulers, presenting materia medica in tabular form across several languages, including Syriac, Persian, Greek, Latin, and Spanish.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Tzvi Langermann, Andalusian medicine evolved distinctive characteristics and, by the 11th century, increasingly shifted away from eastern Islamic models in favour of closer ties with North African traditions.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The influence of Andalusian medicine is evident in later Jewish figures such as Maimonides (1135–1204), whose teachers were trained in this tradition and who himself adopted its emphasis on holistic, Galenic approaches to care.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] In Córdoba, Abd ar-Rahman I built the Great Mosque of Córdoba in 785.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] It was expanded multiple times up until the 10th century, and after the Reconquista it was converted into a Catholic cathedral.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Its key features include a hypostyle hall with marble columns supporting two-tiered arches, a horseshoe-arch mihrab, ribbed domes, a courtyard (*sahn*) with gardens, and a minaret (later converted into a bell tower).
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Abd ar-Rahman III, at the height of his power, began construction of Madinat al-Zahra, a luxurious palace-city to serve as a new capital.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The Umayyads also reconstructed the Roman-era bridge over the Guadalquivir River in Córdoba, while the Almohads later added the Calahorra Tower to the bridge.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The Bab al-Mardum Mosque (later converted to a church) in Toledo is a well-preserved example of a small neighbourhood mosque built at the end of the Caliphate period.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The official workshops of the Caliphate, such as those at Madinat al-Zahra, produced luxury goods for use at court or as gifts for guests, allies, and diplomats, which stimulated artistic production.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Many objects produced in the caliph's workshops later made their way into the collections of museums and Christian cathedrals in Europe.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Among the most famous objects of this period are ivory boxes which are carved with vegetal, figurative, and epigraphic motifs.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Notable surviving examples include the Pyxis of al-Mughira, the Pyxis of Zamora, and the Leyre Casket.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] During the Taifas period, art and culture continued to flourish despite the political fragmentation of al-Andalus.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The Aljaferia Palace of Zaragoza is the most significant palace preserved from this period, featuring complex ornamental arcades and stucco decoration.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] In other cities, a number of important palaces or fortresses were begun or expanded by local dynasties such as the Alcazaba of Málaga and the Alcazaba of Almería.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Other examples of architecture from around this period include the Bañuelo of Granada, an Islamic bathhouse.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] In Seville, Almohad rulers built the Great Mosque of Seville (later transformed into the Cathedral of Seville), which consisted of a hypostyle prayer hall, a courtyard (now known as the *Patio de los Naranjos* or Court of Oranges), and a massive minaret tower now known as the Giralda.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The minaret was later expanded after being converted into a bell tower for the current cathedral.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Almohad architecture promoted new forms and decorative designs such as the multifoil arch and the sebka motif, probably influenced by the Caliphate-period architecture of Córdoba.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Artists and intellectuals took refuge at Granada after the Christian kingdoms expanded significantly in the 13th century.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The palaces of the Alhambra and the Generalife in Granada reflect the culture and art of the last centuries of Muslim rule of al-Andalus.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The complex was begun by Ibn al-Ahmar, the first Nasrid emir, and the last major additions were made during the reigns of Yusuf I (1333–1353) and Muhammad V (1353–1391).
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] It integrates buildings and gardens with the natural qualities of the site and is a testament to Andalusi culture and to the skills of the Muslim artisans, craftsmen, and builders of their era.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Nasrid architecture continued the earlier traditions of Andalusi architecture while also synthesising them into its own distinctive style, which had many similarities with contemporary Marinid architecture in North Africa.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] It is characterised by the use of the courtyard as a central space and basic unit around which other halls and rooms were organised.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Courtyards typically had water features at their centre, such as a reflective pool or a fountain.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Decoration was focused on the inside of buildings and was executed primarily with tile mosaics on lower walls and carved stucco on the upper walls.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Geometric patterns, vegetal motifs, and calligraphy were the main types of decorative motifs.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Additionally, "stalactite"-like sculpting, known as muqarnas, was used for three-dimensional features like vaulted ceilings, particularly during the reign of Muhammad V and after.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Numerous examples are found in the early churches of Toledo (e.g. the Church of San Román, 13th century) and in the cities of Aragon such as Zaragoza and Teruel.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Among the most famous examples is the Alcázar of Seville, the former Abbadid and Almohad palace redeveloped by Christian rulers such as Peter of Castile, who in 1364 started adding new Moorish-style sections with the help of Muslim craftsmen from Granada and Toledo.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Some surviving 13th and 14th-century Jewish synagogues were also built (or rebuilt) in Mudéjar style under Christian rule, such as the Synagogue of Santa Maria la Blanca in Toledo (rebuilt in its current form circa 1250), the Synagogue of Córdoba (1315), and the Synagogue of El Tránsito (1355–1357).
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Crops produced using irrigation, along with food imported from the Middle East, provided areas around *Andalusī* cities with an agricultural economic sector that was the most advanced in Europe by far, sparking the Arab Agricultural Revolution.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] A variety of foodstuffs, spices and crops were introduced to Spain and Sicily during Arab rule, via the commercial networks of the Islamic world.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] These include sugarcane, rice, cotton, alfalfa, oranges, lemons, apricots, spinach, eggplants, carrots, saffron and bananas.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The Arabs also continued extensive cultivation and production of olive oil (the Spanish words for 'oil' and 'olive'—*aceite* and *aceituna*, respectively—are derived from the Arabic *al-zait*, meaning 'olive juice'), and pomegranates (the heraldic symbol of Granada) from classical Greco-Roman times.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Arabic influence still lingers on in Spanish cuisine through these fruits, vegetables, spices and cooking and agricultural techniques.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] These structures are still found in Andalusia province, particularly in Granada.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The confection *alfajor* (supposedly from الفاخر) has its origins in al-Andalus.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Important rulers such as Abd al-Rahman III, al-Hakam II, Hisham II, and al-Mu-tamid openly chose boys as sexual partners, and kept catamites.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Homosexual prostitution was widespread, and its customers came from higher levels of society than those of heterosexual prostitutes." The verses of Ibn Quzman describe an openly bisexual lifestyle.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Andalusi anthologies of poetry such as the *Rāyāt al-mubarrizīn wa-ghāyāt al-mumayyazīn* are known in part for their homoerotic and "abundant pederastic poetry".
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Such themes were also found in the Sephardic Jewish poetry of the time.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] In the book *Medieval Iberia: An Encyclopedia*, Daniel Eisenberg describes homosexuality as "a key symbolic issue throughout the Middle Ages in Iberia", stating that "in al-Andalus homosexual pleasures were much indulged in by the intellectual and political elite.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Both pederasty and love between adult males are found.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Although homosexual practices were never officially condoned, prohibitions against them were rarely enforced, and usually there was not even a pretense of doing so." Male homosexual relations allowed nonprocreative sexual practices and were not seen as a form of identity.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Very little is known about the homosexual behaviour of women.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Slavery existed in Muslim al-Andalus as well as in the Christian kingdoms, and both sides of the religious border followed the custom of not enslaving people of their own religion.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Consequently, Muslims were enslaved in Christian lands, while Christians and other non-Muslims were enslaved in al-Andalus.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The Moors imported white Christian slaves from the 8th century until the end of the Reconquista in the late 15th century.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The slaves were exported from the Christian section of Spain, as well as Eastern Europe (*Saqaliba*).
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Saqaliba slavery in al-Andalus was especially prominent in the Caliphate of Córdoba where white slaves constituted most of the administrative personnel in the courts and palaces.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The slaves of the Caliph were often European saqaliba slaves trafficked from Northern or Eastern Europe.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] While male saqaliba could be given work in a number of tasks, such as offices in the kitchen, falconry, mint, textile workshops, the administration or the royal guard (in the case of harem guards, they were castrated), female saqaliba were placed in the harem.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The harem could contain thousands of slave concubines; the harem of Abd al-Rahman I consisted of 6,300 women.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] They were appreciated for their light skin.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] The concubines (jawaris) were educated in accomplishments to please their master, and many became known and respected for their knowledge in a variety of subjects from music to medicine.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Jawaris concubines who gave birth to a child attained the status of an *umm walad*, which meant that they could no longer be sold and were to be set free after the death of her master.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] As Andalusi cities were conquered by Leon, Castile, and other Christian Spanish kingdoms, Christian monarchs such as Alfonso X of Castile started translating the mountainous libraries of al-Andalus into Latin.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] These libraries contained translations of Ancient Greek texts, as well as new ones made by Muslims in the Islamic Golden Age.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] That, combined with the interaction with Muslims during the Crusades, and the Fall of Constantinople introducing Greek scholars to the west, helped launch the Renaissance.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Scientists and philosophers such as Averroes and Al-Zahrawi (fathers of rationalism and surgery, respectively) heavily inspired the Renaissance, and their ideas are still world renowned to this day.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Al Andalus has also left art and architecture and has some of the best preserved Islamic Golden Age architecture in the world, with examples including the Cathedral of Córdoba, the Alhambra, the Giralda and many more.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] As a result of the Reconquista and fall of many important Andalusi cities, substantial numbers of Andalusi migrated to the Maghreb where they found place at the courts of Maghrebi rulers.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] Many of the elite Andalusi immigrants were Arabs.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] For a variety of reasons, "Andalusi" came to be almost synonymous with "Arab" in the Maghreb.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] In the Iberian Peninsula, many Muslims were forced to convert to Christianity, particularly in the latter period of the Reconquista and following the decrees of 1502 and 1526.
[src:archimedes-screw/al-andalus-p02] These converts and their descendants, known as Moriscos, remained under intense persecution until their expulsion in the early 17th century.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Aside from geometry, Apollonius worked on numerous other topics, including astronomy.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Most of this work has not survived, where exceptions are typically fragments referenced by other authors like Pappus of Alexandria.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] His hypothesis of eccentric orbits to explain the apparently aberrant motion of the planets, commonly believed until the Middle Ages, was superseded during the Renaissance.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The Apollonius crater on the Moon is named in his honor.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Despite his momentous contributions to the field of mathematics, scant biographical information on Apollonius remains.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] From this passage Apollonius can be approximately dated, but specific birth and death years stated by modern scholars are only speculative.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Ptolemy III Euergetes ("benefactor") was third Greek dynast of Egypt in the Diadochi succession, who reigned 246–222/221 BC.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] "Times" are always recorded by ruler or officiating magistrate, so Apollonius was likely born after 246.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The identity of Herakleios is uncertain.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Perga was a Hellenized city in Pamphylia, Anatolia, whose ruins yet stand.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Eutocius appears to associate Perga with the Ptolemaic dynasty of Egypt.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Never under Egypt, Perga in 246 BC belonged to the Seleucid Empire, an independent diadochi state ruled by the Seleucid dynasty.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] During the last half of the 3rd century BC, Perga changed hands a number of times, being alternatively under the Seleucids and under the Attalids of Pergamon to the north.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Someone designated "of Perga" might be expected to have lived and worked there; to the contrary, if Apollonius was later identified with Perga, it was not on the basis of his residence.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The remaining autobiographical material implies that he lived, studied, and wrote in Alexandria.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] A letter by the Greek mathematician and astronomer Hypsicles was originally part of the supplement taken from a pseudepigraphic work transmitted as *Book XIV* of Euclid's *Elements*.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Some autobiographical material can be found in the surviving prefaces to the books of *Conics.* These are letters Apollonius addressed to influential friends asking them to review the book enclosed with the letter.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The first two prefaces are addressed to Eudemus of Pergamon.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Eudemus likely was or became the head of the research center of the *Museum* of Pergamon, a city known for its books and parchment industry from which the name *parchment* is derived.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Research in Greek mathematical institutions, which followed the model of the Athenian Lycaeum, was part of the educational effort to which the library and museum were adjunct.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] There was only one such school in the state, under royal patronage.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Books were rare and expensive and collecting them was a royal obligation.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Apollonius's preface to Book I tells Eudemus that the first four books were concerned with the development of elements while the last four were concerned with special topics.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Apollonius reminds Eudemus that *Conics* was initially requested by Naucrates, a geometer and house guest at Alexandria otherwise unknown to history.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Apollonius provided Naucrates the first draft of all eight books, but he refers to them as being "without a thorough purgation", and intended to verify and correct the books, releasing each one as it was completed.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Having heard this plan from Apollonius himself, who visited Pergamon, Eudemus insisted Apollonius send him each book before release.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] At this stage Apollonius was likely still a young geometer, who according to Pappus stayed at Alexandria with the students of Euclid (long after Euclid's time), perhaps the final stage of his education.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Eudemus may have been a mentor from Apollonius's time in Pergamon.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] There is a gap between the first and second prefaces.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Apollonius has sent his son, also named Apollonius, to deliver the second.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] He speaks with more confidence, suggesting that Eudemus use the book in special study groups.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Apollonius mentions meeting Philonides of Laodicea, a geometer whom he introduced to Eudemus in Ephesus, and who became Eudemus's student.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Philonides lived mainly in Syria during the 1st half of the 2nd century BC.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The preface to Book III is missing, and during the interval Eudemus died, says Apollonius in the preface to Book IV.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Prefaces to Books IV–VII are more formal, mere summaries omitting personal information.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] All four are addressed to a mysterious Attalus, a choice made, Apollonius says, "because of your earnest desire to possess my works".
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Presumably Attalus was important to be sent Apollonius's manuscripts.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] One theory is that Attalus is Attalus II Philadelphus (220–138 BC), general and defender of Pergamon whose brother Eumenes II was king, and who became co-regent after his brother's illness in 160 BC and acceded to the throne in 158 BC.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Both brothers were patrons of the arts, expanding the library into international magnificence.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Attalus was a contemporary of Philonides and Apollonius's motive is consonant with Attalus's book-collecting initiative.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] In Preface VII Apollonius describes Book VIII as "an appendix ... which I will take care to send you as speedily as possible." There is no record that it was ever sent, and Apollonius might have died before finishing it.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Pappus of Alexandria, however, provided lemmas for it, so it must have been in circulation in some form.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Apollonius was a prolific geometer, turning out a large number of works.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Of its eight books, only the first four persist as untranslated original texts of Apollonius.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Books 5-7 are only preserved via an Arabic translation by Thābit ibn Qurra commissioned by the Banū Mūsā; the original Greek is lost.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] A first draft existed, but whether the final draft was ever produced is not known.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] A "reconstruction" of it by Edmond Halley exists in Latin, but there is no way to know how much of it, if any, is verisimilar to Apollonius.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Other than a single other work surviving in Arabic translation, *De Rationis Sectione*, The rest of Apollonius's works are fragmentary or lost.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Many of the lost works are described or mentioned by commentators, especially Pappus of Alexandria, who provides epitomes and lemmas for many of Apollonius's lost works in book 7 of his collection.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Based on Pappus's summaries, Edmond Halley reconstructed *De Spatii Sectione*.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The Greek text of *Conics* uses the Euclidean arrangement of definitions, figures and their parts; i.e., the “givens,” followed by propositions “to be proved.” Books I-VII present 387 propositions.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] This type of arrangement can be seen in any modern geometry textbook of the traditional subject matter.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] As in any course of mathematics, the material is very dense and consideration of it, necessarily slow.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Apollonius had a plan for each book, which is partly described in the *Prefaces*.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The headings, or pointers to the plan, are somewhat in deficit, Apollonius having depended more on the logical flow of the topics.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Its most salient content is all the basic definitions concerning cones and conic sections.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] These definitions are not exactly the same as the modern ones of the same words.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Etymologically the modern words derive from the ancient, but the etymon often differs in meaning from its reflex.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] A conical surface is generated by a line segment rotated about a bisector point such that the end points trace circles, each in its own plane.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] A cone, one branch of the double conical surface, is the surface with the point (apex or vertex), the circle (base), and the axis, a line joining vertex and center of base.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] A *section* (Latin *sectio*, Greek *tome*) is an imaginary "cutting" of a cone by a plane.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The "application of areas" implicitly asks, given an area and a line segment, does this area apply; that is, is it equal to, the square on the segment?
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] If yes, an applicability (parabole) has been established.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Apollonius followed Euclid in asking if a rectangle on the abscissa of any point on the section applies to the square of the ordinate.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] If it does, his word-equation is the equivalent of ${\textstyle y^{2}=kx}$ which is one modern form of the equation for a parabola.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] It was he who accordingly named the figure, parabola, "application".
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The "no applicability" case is further divided into two possibilities.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Given a function, ${\textstyle f(x)}$ , such that, in the applicability case, ${\textstyle y^{2}=g(x)}$ , in the no applicability case, either ${\textstyle y^{2}>g(x)}$ or ${\textstyle y^{2}<g(x)}$ .
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] In the former, $g(x)$ falls short of ${\textstyle y^{2}}$ by a quantity termed the *ellipsis*, "deficit".
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] In the latter, $g(x)$ overshoots by a quantity termed the *hyperbole*, "surfeit".
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Applicability could be achieved by adding the deficit, ${\textstyle y^{2}=f(x)=g(x)+d,}$ or subtracting the surfeit, $g(x)-s.$ The figure compensating for a deficit was named an ellipse; for a surfeit, a hyperbola.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The elements mentioned are those that specify the shape and generation of the figures.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Tangents are covered at the end of the book.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Apollonius claims original discovery for theorems "of use for the construction of solid loci ... the three-line and four-line locus ...." The locus of a conic section is the section.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The four-line problem results in the ellipse and hyperbola.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Analytic geometry derives the same loci from simpler criteria supported by algebra, rather than geometry, for which Descartes was highly praised.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] He supersedes Apollonius in his methods.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The first sent to Attalus, rather than to Eudemus, it thus represents his more mature geometric thought.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The topic is rather specialized: "the greatest number of points at which sections of a cone can meet one another, or meet a circumference of a circle, ...." Nevertheless, he speaks with enthusiasm, labeling them "of considerable use" in solving problems (Preface 4).
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] In contrast to Book I, Book V contains no definitions and no explanation.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] It contains 77 propositions, the most of any book, dealing with maximum and minimum lines.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] However, more recent scholarship has shown that these are standard terms used in Ancient Greek mathematics to refer to maximum and minimum distances.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Book VI, known only through translation from the Arabic, contains 33 propositions, the least of any book.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] It also has large lacunae, or gaps in the text, due to damage or corruption in the previous texts.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Preface 1 states that the topic is “equal and similar sections of cones.” Apollonius extends the concepts of congruence and similarity presented by Euclid for more elementary figures, such as triangles, quadrilaterals, to conic sections.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Preface 6 mentions “sections and segments” that are “equal and unequal” as well as “similar and dissimilar,” and adds some constructional information.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Book VI features a return to the basic definitions at the front of the book. “Equality” is determined by an application of areas.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] If one figure; that is, a section or a segment, is “applied” to another, they are “equal” if they coincide and no line of one crosses any line of the other.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] In Apollonius's definitions at the beginning of Book VI, similar right cones have similar axial triangles.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Similar sections and segments of sections are first of all in similar cones.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] In addition, for every abscissa of one must exist an abscissa in the other at the desired scale.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Finally, abscissa and ordinate of one must be matched by coordinates of the same ratio of ordinate to abscissa as the other.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The total effect is as though the section or segment were moved up and down the cone to achieve a different scale.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Book VII, also a translation from the Arabic, contains 51 Propositions.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] In Preface I, Apollonius does not mention them, implying that, at the time of the first draft, they may not have existed in sufficiently coherent form to describe.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The topic of Book VII is stated in Preface VII to be diameters and “the figures described upon them.” The 51 propositions of Book VII define the relationships between sections, diameters, and conjugate diameters.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Apollonius uses obscure language, that they are “peri dioristikon theorematon” lit.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Each of these was divided into two books, and—with the *Data*, the *Porisms*, and *Surface-Loci* of Euclid and the *Conics* of Apollonius—were, according to Pappus, included in the body of the ancient analysis.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Descriptions follow of the six works mentioned above.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The object of *Neusis* was to demonstrate how a straight line of a given length, tending towards a given point, could be inserted between two given (straight or circular) lines.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Though Marin Getaldić and Hugo d'Omerique (*Geometrical Analysis*, Cadiz, 1698) attempted restorations, the best is by Samuel Horsley (1770).
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] According to Heath, the "Methods of Apollonius" were not personal to him; whatever influence he had on later theorists was the influence of geometry, not of his own innovation of technique.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] When referring to golden age geometers, modern scholars use the term "method" to mean the visual, reconstructive way in which the geometer produces a result equivalent to that produced by algebra today.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] As a simple example, the algebraic method to compute the area of a square is to square its side length; the analogous geometric method is to construct a visual square.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Geometric methods in the golden age could produce most of the results of elementary algebra.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The equivalence of two descriptions of planet motions, one using eccentrics and another deferent and epicycles, is attributed to Apollonius.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Ptolemy describes this equivalence in the *Almagest*.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Heath goes on to use the term *geometrical algebra* for the methods of the entire golden age.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The term had been defined by Henry Burchard Fine in 1890 or before, who applied it to La Géométrie of René Descartes, the first full-blown work of analytic geometry.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Establishing as a precondition that “two algebras are formally identical whose fundamental operations are formally the same,” Fine says that Descartes's work “is not ... mere numerical algebra, but what may for want of a better name be called the algebra of line segments.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Its symbolism is the same as that of numerical algebra; ...”.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] For example, in Apollonius a line segment AB (the line between Point A and Point B) is also the numerical length of the segment.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] AB therefore becomes the same as an algebraic variable, such as *x* (the unknown), to which any value might be assigned; e.g., *x*=3.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Variables are defined in Apollonius by such word statements as “let AB be the distance from any point on the section to the diameter,” a practice that continues in algebra today.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Every student of basic algebra must learn to convert “word problems” to algebraic variables and equations, to which the rules of algebra apply in solving for *x*.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Relationships not readily amenable to pictorial solutions were beyond his grasp; however, his repertory of pictorial solutions came from a pool of complex geometric solutions generally not known (or required) today.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] One well-known exception is the indispensable Pythagorean theorem, even now represented by a right triangle with squares on its sides illustrating an expression such as a2 + b2 = c2.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The Greek geometers called those terms “the square on AB,” etc.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] These concepts gave the Greek geometers algebraic access to linear functions and quadratic functions, which latter the conic sections are.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] They contain powers of 1 or 2 respectively.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Apollonius had not much use for cubes (featured in solid geometry), even though a cone is a solid.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] His interest was in conic sections, which are plane figures.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Powers of 4 and up were beyond visualization, requiring a degree of abstraction not available in geometry, but ready at hand in algebra.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] All ordinary measurement of length in public units, such as inches, using standard public devices, such as a ruler, implies public recognition of a Cartesian grid; that is, a surface divided into unit squares, such as one square inch, and a space divided into unit cubes, such as one cubic inch.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The ancient Greek units of measurement had provided such a grid to Greek mathematicians since the Bronze Age.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] These edges of the window become, in the Cartesian coordinate system, the axes.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] One specifies the rectilinear distances of any point from the axes as the coordinates.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The ancient Greeks did not have that convention.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Apollonius does have a standard window in which he places his figures.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Vertical measurement is from a horizontal line he calls the “diameter.” The word is the same in Greek as it is in English, but the Greek is somewhat wider in its comprehension.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] If the figure of the conic section is cut by a grid of parallel lines, the diameter bisects all the line segments included between the branches of the figure.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] It must pass through the vertex (koruphe, "crown").
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] A diameter thus comprises open figures such as a parabola as well as closed, such as a circle.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] There is no specification that the diameter must be perpendicular to the parallel lines, but Apollonius uses only rectilinear ones.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The rectilinear distance from a point on the section to the diameter is termed tetagmenos in Greek, etymologically simply “extended.” As it is only ever extended “down” (kata-) or “up” (ana-), the translators interpret it as ordinate.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] In that case the diameter becomes the x-axis and the vertex the origin.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The y-axis then becomes a tangent to the curve at the vertex.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The abscissa is then defined as the segment of the diameter between the ordinate and the vertex.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Using his version of a coordinate system, Apollonius manages to develop in pictorial form the geometric equivalents of the equations for the conic sections, which raises the question of whether his coordinate system can be considered Cartesian.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The Cartesian system is to be regarded as universal, covering all figures in all space applied before any calculation is done.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] It has four quadrants divided by the two crossed axes.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Three of the quadrants include negative coordinates meaning directions opposite the reference axes of zero.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Apollonius has no negative numbers, does not explicitly have a number for zero, and does not develop the coordinate system independently of the conic sections.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] He works essentially only in Quadrant 1, all positive coordinates.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Nevertheless, according to Boyer, Apollonius's treatment of curves is in some ways similar to the modern treatment, and his work seems to anticipate analytical geometry.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Apollonius occupies some sort of intermediate niche between the grid system of conventional measurement and the fully developed Cartesian Coordinate System of Analytic Geometry.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] In reading Apollonius, one must take care not to assume modern meanings for his terms.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Apollonius uses the "Theory of Proportions" as expressed in Euclid’s *Elements*, Books 5 and 6.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Devised by Eudoxus of Cnidus, the theory is intermediate between purely graphic methods and modern number theory.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] A standard decimal number system is lacking, as is a standard treatment of fractions.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The propositions, however, express in words rules for manipulating fractions in arithmetic.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Heath proposes that they stand in place of multiplication and division.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] By the term “magnitude” Eudoxus hoped to go beyond numbers to a general sense of size, a meaning it still retains.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] With regard to the figures of Euclid, it most often means numbers, which was the Pythagorean approach.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Pythagoras believed the universe could be characterized by quantities, which belief has become the current scientific dogma.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Book V of Euclid begins by insisting that a magnitude (megethos, “size”) must be divisible evenly into units (meros, “part”).
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] A magnitude is thus a multiple of units.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] They do not have to be standard measurement units, such as meters or feet.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] One unit can be any designated line segment.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] There follows perhaps the most useful fundamental definition ever devised in science: the ratio (Greek logos, meaning roughly “explanation.”) is a statement of relative magnitude.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Given two magnitudes, say of segments AB and CD. the ratio of AB to CD, where CD is considered unit, is the number of CD in AB; for example, 3 parts of 4, or 60 parts per million, where ppm still uses the “parts” terminology.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The ratio is the basis of the modern fraction, which also still means “part,” or “fragment”, from the same Latin root as fracture.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The ratio is the basis of mathematical prediction in the logical structure called a “proportion” (Greek analogos).
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The proportion states that if two segments, AB and CD, have the same ratio as two others, EF and GH, then AB and CD are proportional to EF and GH, or, as would be said in Euclid, AB is to CD as EF is to GH.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Algebra reduces this general concept to the expression AB/CD = EF/GH.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Given any three of the terms, one can calculate the fourth as an unknown.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Rearranging the above equation, one obtains AB = (CD/GH)•EF, in which, expressed as y = kx, the CD/GH is known as the “constant of proportionality.” The Greeks had little difficulty with taking multiples (Greek pollaplasiein), probably by successive addition.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Apollonius uses ratios almost exclusively of line segments and areas, which are designated by squares and rectangles.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The translators have undertaken to use the colon notation introduced by Leibniz in *Acta Eruditorum*, 1684.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Taliaferro’s translation: “Let it be contrived that sq.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] The *Conics* exerted an influence on later geometry during Classical antiquity, through the medieval and modern era.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] In the 4th century, Serenus of Antinoöpolis wrote a commentary on the *Conics*, which has been lost, along with two shorter works still extant on parts of the Conics: *On the Section of a Cylinder* and *On the Section of a Cone*.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] In the 6th century, Eutocius of Ascalon wrote a commentary on the *Conics* books I-IV, which is extant.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] In the 9th century, the Banū Mūsā commissioned an Arabic translation of the *Conics*.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Books I–IV of Apollonius's Conics were first printed in Latin in 1566.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] In 1626, Jacobus Golius discovered a surviving copy of the Arabic translation of Books V–VI, which was eventually donated to the Bodleian Library (originally as MS Marsh 607, dated 1070).
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Encouraged by the success of his translation of David Gregory's emended Arabic text of *Cutting off a Ratio*, published in 1706, Halley went on to restore and translate into Latin Apollonius's entire *Conics*, including a reconstruction of Book VIII from Pappus's summary.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] In Halley's work, Books I–IV appear with the Greek in one column and Halley's Latin in a parallel column, while only the Latin translation of Books V–VII is given.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Halley's reconstruction is printed in Latin.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] During the 16th–18th century, limited material about *Conics* was ever written in English, because English mathematicians, such as Edmund Halley and Isaac Newton, preferred Neo-Latin.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] In later centuries, geometry was re-established using coordinates (analytic geometry) and synthetic methods fell out of favor, so *Conics*' direct influence on mathematical research declined.
[src:archimedes-screw/apollonius-of-perga] Presentations written entirely in native English begin in the late 19th century.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] The **Archimedean solids** are a set of thirteen convex polyhedra whose faces are regular polygons and are vertex-transitive, although they are not face-transitive.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] The solids were named after Archimedes, although he did not claim credit for them.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] They belong to the class of uniform polyhedra, the polyhedra with regular faces and symmetric vertices.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] Some Archimedean solids were portrayed in the works of artists and mathematicians during the Renaissance.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] The elongated square gyrobicupola or *pseudo­rhombi­cub­octa­hedron* is an extra polyhedron with regular faces and congruent vertices.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] Still, it is not generally counted as an Archimedean solid because it is not vertex-transitive.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] The Archimedean solids have a single vertex configuration and highly symmetric properties.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] A vertex configuration indicates which regular polygons meet at each vertex.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] For instance, the configuration $3\cdot 5\cdot 3\cdot 5$ indicates a polyhedron in which each vertex is met by alternating two triangles and two pentagons.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] Highly symmetric properties in this case mean the symmetry group of each solid was derived from the Platonic solids, resulting from their construction.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] Some sources say the Archimedean solids are synonymous with the semiregular polyhedron.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] Yet, the definition of a semiregular polyhedron may also include the infinite families of prisms and antiprisms, including the elongated square gyrobicupola.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] The skeleton of Archimedean solids can be drawn in a graph, named Archimedean graph.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] Such graphs are regular, polyhedral (and therefore by necessity also 3-vertex-connected planar graphs), and also Hamiltonian graphs.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] The construction of some Archimedean solids begins from the Platonic solids.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] If the truncation is exactly deep enough such that each pair of faces from adjacent vertices shares exactly one point, it is known as a rectification.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] Expansion involves moving each face away from the center (by the same distance to preserve the symmetry of the Platonic solid) and taking the convex hull.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] An example is the rhombicuboctahedron, which is constructed by separating the cube or octahedron's faces from their centroids and filling them with squares.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] Snub is a construction process of polyhedra by separating the polyhedron faces, twisting their faces in certain angles, and filling them up with equilateral triangles.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] Examples can be found in snub cube and snub dodecahedron.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] The resulting construction of these solids gives the property of chirality, meaning they are not identical when reflected in a mirror.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] However, not all of them can be constructed in such a way, or they could be constructed alternatively.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] For example, the icosidodecahedron can be constructed by attaching two pentagonal rotunda bases-to-base, or a rhombicuboctahedron that can be constructed alternatively by attaching two square cupolas on the bases of an octagonal prism.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] At least ten of the Archimedean solids have the Rupert property: each can pass through a copy of itself, of the same size.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] They are the cuboctahedron, truncated octahedron, truncated cube, rhombicuboctahedron, icosidodecahedron, truncated cuboctahedron, truncated icosahedron, truncated dodecahedron, and the truncated tetrahedron.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] The dual polyhedron of an Archimedean solid is a Catalan solid.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] The names of Archimedean solids were taken from the Ancient Greek mathematician Archimedes, who discussed them in a now-lost work.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] Although they were not credited to Archimedes originally, Pappus of Alexandria in the fifth section of his titled compendium *Synagoge*, referring to Archimedes, listed thirteen polyhedra and briefly described them in terms of how many faces of each kind these polyhedra have.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] During the Renaissance, artists and mathematicians valued pure forms with high symmetry.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] Some Archimedean solids appeared in Piero della Francesca's *De quinque corporibus regularibus*, in attempting to study and copy the works of Archimedes, as well as include citations to Archimedes.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] Yet, he did not credit those shapes to Archimedes and knew of Archimedes' work, but rather appeared to be an independent rediscovery.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] Other appearance of the solids appeared in the works of Wenzel Jamnitzer's *Perspectiva Corporum Regularium*, and both *Summa de arithmetica* and *Divina proportione* by Luca Pacioli, drawn by Leonardo da Vinci.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] The net of Archimedean solids appeared in Albrecht Dürer's *Underweysung der Messung*, copied from the Pacioli's work.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] By around 1620, Johannes Kepler in his *Harmonices Mundi* had completed the rediscovery of the thirteen polyhedra, as well as defining the prisms, antiprisms, and the non-convex solids known as Kepler–Poinsot polyhedra.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] The latter is not vertex-transitive, and thus not Archimedean.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] Kepler may have also found another solid known as elongated square gyrobicupola or *pseudorhombicuboctahedron*.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] Kepler once stated that there were fourteen Archimedean solids, yet his published enumeration only includes the thirteen uniform polyhedra.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] The first clear statement of such solid existence was made by Duncan Sommerville in 1905.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] The solid appeared when some mathematicians mistakenly constructed the rhombicuboctahedron: two square cupolas attached to the octagonal prism, with one of them rotated forty-five degrees.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] The thirteen solids have the property of vertex-transitive, meaning any two vertices of those can be translated onto the other one, but the elongated square gyrobicupola does not.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] Grünbaum pointed out a frequent error in which authors define Archimedean solids using some form of this local definition but omit the fourteenth polyhedron.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] If only thirteen polyhedra are to be listed, the definition must use global symmetries of the polyhedron rather than local neighborhoods.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-solid] In the aftermath, the elongated square gyrobicupola was withdrawn from the Archimedean solids and included in the Johnson solids instead, a convex polyhedron in which all of the faces are regular polygons.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] The **Archimedean spiral** (also known as **Archimedes' spiral**, the **arithmetic spiral**) is a spiral named after the 3rd-century BC Greek mathematician Archimedes.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] The term *Archimedean spiral* is sometimes used to refer to the more general class of spirals of this type (see below), in contrast to *Archimedes' spiral* (the specific arithmetic spiral of Archimedes).
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] It is the locus corresponding to the locations over time of a point moving away from a fixed point with a constant speed along a line that rotates with constant angular velocity.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Equivalently, in polar coordinates (*r*, *θ*) it can be described by the equation $r=b\cdot \theta$ with real number b.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Changing the parameter b controls the distance between loops.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] From the above equation, it can thus be stated: position of the particle from point of start is proportional to angle θ as time elapses.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Archimedes described such a spiral in his book *On Spirals*.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Conon of Samos was a friend of his and Pappus states that this spiral was discovered by Conon.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] A physical approach is used below to understand the notion of Archimedean spirals.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Suppose a point object moves in the Cartesian system with a constant velocity v directed parallel to the x-axis, with respect to the xy-plane.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Let at time *t* = 0, the object was at an arbitrary point (*c*, 0, 0).
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] As shown in the figure alongside, we have *vt* + *c* representing the modulus of the position vector of the particle at any time t, with vx and vy as the velocity components along the x and y axes, respectively.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] The Archimedean spiral has the property that any ray from the origin intersects successive turnings of the spiral in points with a constant separation distance (equal to 2*πb* if θ is measured in radians), hence the name "arithmetic spiral".
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] In contrast to this, in a logarithmic spiral these distances, as well as the distances of the intersection points measured from the origin, form a geometric progression.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] The Archimedean spiral has two arms, one for *θ* > 0 and one for *θ* < 0.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] The two arms are smoothly connected at the origin.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Only one arm is shown on the accompanying graph.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Taking the mirror image of this arm across the y-axis will yield the other arm.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] As the Archimedean spiral grows, its evolute asymptotically approaches a circle with radius ⁠|*v*|/*ω*⁠.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] The normal Archimedean spiral occurs when *c* = 1.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Other spirals falling into this group include the hyperbolic spiral (*c* = −1), Fermat's spiral (*c* = 2), and the lituus (*c* = −2).
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] One method of squaring the circle, due to Archimedes, makes use of an Archimedean spiral.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Archimedes also showed how the spiral can be used to trisect an angle.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Both approaches relax the traditional limitations on the use of straightedge and compass in ancient Greek geometric proofs.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] The Archimedean spiral has a variety of real-world applications.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Scroll compressors, used for compressing gases, have rotors that can be made from two interleaved Archimedean spirals, involutes of a circle of the same size that almost resemble Archimedean spirals, or hybrid curves.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Archimedean spirals can be found in spiral antenna, which can be operated over a wide range of frequencies.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] The coils of watch balance springs and the grooves of very early gramophone records form Archimedean spirals, making the grooves evenly spaced (although variable track spacing was later introduced to maximize the amount of music that could be cut onto a record).
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Asking for a patient to draw an Archimedean spiral is a way of quantifying human tremor; this information helps in diagnosing neurological diseases.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Archimedean spirals are also used in digital light processing (DLP) projection systems to minimize the "rainbow effect", making it look as if multiple colors are displayed at the same time, when in reality red, green, and blue are being cycled extremely quickly.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Additionally, Archimedean spirals are used in food microbiology to quantify bacterial concentration through a spiral platter.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] They are also used to model the pattern that occurs in a roll of paper or tape of constant thickness wrapped around a cylinder.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Many dynamic spirals (such as the Parker spiral of the solar wind, or the pattern made by a Catherine's wheel) are Archimedean.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] For instance, the star LL Pegasi shows an approximate Archimedean spiral in the dust clouds surrounding it, thought to be ejected matter from the star that has been shepherded into a spiral by another companion star as part of a double star system.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] The Archimedean Spiral cannot be constructed precisely by traditional compass and straightedge methods, since the arithmetic spiral requires the radius of the curve to be incremented constantly as the angle at the origin is incremented.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] But an arithmetic spiral can be constructed approximately, to varying degrees of precision, by various manual drawing methods.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] One such method uses compass and straightedge; another method uses a modified string compass.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] The common traditional construction uses compass and straightedge to approximate the arithmetic spiral.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] First, a large circle is constructed and its circumference is subdivided by 12 diameters into 12 arcs (of 30 degrees each; see regular dodecagon).
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Next, the radius of this circle is itself subdivided into 12 unit segments (radial units), and a series of concentric circles is constructed, each with radius incremented by one radial unit.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] After all points have been marked, successive points are connected by a line approximating the arithmetic spiral (or by a smooth curve of some sort; see French Curve).
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Depending on the desired degree of precision, this method can be improved by increasing the size of the large outer circle, making more subdivisions of both its circumference and radius, increasing the number of concentric circles (see Polygonal Spiral).
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Approximating the Archimedean Spiral by this method is of course reminiscent of Archimedes’ famous method of approximating π by doubling the sides of successive polygons (see Polygon approximation of π).
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Compass and straightedge construction of the Spiral of Theodorus is another simple method to approximate the Archimedean Spiral.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Such a method is a simple way to create an arithmetic spiral, arising naturally from use of a string compass with winding pin (not the loose pivot of a common string compass).
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] The string compass drawing tool has various modifications and designs, and this construction method is reminiscent of string-based methods for creating ellipses (with two fixed pins).
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] Yet another mechanical method is a variant of the previous string compass method, providing greater precision and more flexibility.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] The two arms rotate together and work in consort to produce the arithmetic spiral: as the horizontal arm gradually climbs the screw, that arm’s slotted attachment to the sloped arm gradually shortens the drawing radius.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] The angle of the sloped arm remains constant throughout (traces a cone), and setting a different angle varies the pitch of the spiral.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] This device provides a high degree of precision, depending on the precision with which the device is machined (machining a precise helical screw thread is a related challenge).
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedean-spiral] And of course the use of a screw shaft in this mechanism is reminiscent of Archimedes’ screw.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] An **Archimedes' screw** is a hydraulic machine composing of an outer cylinder and an inner cylinder with helical blades.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] It can be operated both as a pump and a power generator, though it has been used for other purposes, such as drainage and sewage management.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] The origins of the water screw are unknown; Archimedes of Syracuse is traditionally credited with inventing the water screw, but other academics argue Archimedes found the Egyptians already using the screw.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] The earliest mention of the screw is from between 250 and 220 BC, and archaeological remains of water screws in Europe and Asia suggested that it was diffused across the territories of the Roman Empire, though the screw largely fell out of use in Europe in the third century AD.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] However, it resurfaced during Renaissance, with the screw introduced to other regions such as China and Japan.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] In 1991, a patent for the Archimedes screw turbine was filed, and the testing was done between 1993 and 1995.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] As a machine used for lifting water from a low-lying body of water into irrigation ditches, it lifts water by turning a screw-shaped surface inside a pipe.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] In the modern world, Archimedes' screw pumps are widely used in wastewater treatment plants and for dewatering low-lying regions.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Run in reverse, Archimedes screw turbines act as a small hydroelectric powerplant that can be applied even in low head sites.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Such generators operate in a wide range of flows (0.01 m3/s to 14.5 m3/s) and heads (0.1 m to 10 m), including low heads and moderate flow rates that are not ideal for traditional turbines and not occupied by high performance technologies.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] The origins of the water screw are unknown; Archimedes is credited with inventing the water screw, but it is controversial amongst historians.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] According to Posidonius, Archimedes invented the water screw when he visited Egypt, possibly between 283 and 246 BC, with academics arguing that he invented the water screw based on a water wheel he saw in operation.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] 250 BC", and argues that there may have been confusion over terms used by Posidonius.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Scholars also argue that Archimedes's investigations into spirals and the quadrature of a circle led to the development of the Archimedes' screw.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] An Archimedes' screw, under Dalley's supervision, was constructed from Sennacherib's inscription as part of a BBC documentary to determine if the screw was known in Assyria, with Oleson supervising the construction of a screw using Vitruvius's description in *De Architectura*.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Moschion reported in *Treatise on the Great Ship of Hieron of Syracuse*, written between 250 and 220 BC, that the screw was used as a bilge pump in a ship built for Hiero II of Syracuse, and Posidonius also recorded water screws in Spanish mines used for drainage.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] By the late 1st century BC or 1st century AD, there were not many records mentioning the screw, according to Oleson's investigation in Fayum; he posits that they were either uncommon in the city or were not taxed, and hence were not recorded.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Diodorus describes the Archimedes' screw usage for irrigation in the Nile Delta for nearby military camps and cities in his *Bibliotheca Historica*, and Vitruvius details a wooden Archimedes' screw with eight blades in his *De Architectura*, written between 27–22 BC.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] The earliest depiction of the water screw is a fresco at the villa Casa di P.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Cornelius Teges in Pompeii dating earlier than 79 AD.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Archimedes' screw continued to be used in Europe until it fell out of use in the end of the third century.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Historian Lynn White Jr. posits that the screw continued to be used in Visigothic and Islamic Spain, with Oleson theorising that the Arabs may have reintroduced the screw to Europe following the conquest of Spain in the 8th century.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] The first illustration of the Archimedes' screw after antiquity was from German engineer Konrad Kyeser in his 1405 manuscript *Bellifortis*.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] During the Renaissance, scientists such as Leonardo da Vinci and Agostino Ramelli depicted on the Archimedes' screw in several of their "theatre of machine" books, which catalogued machines, and Galileo Galilei explained the function of the Archimedes' screw in his *Mecchanice*.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Polder mills, consisting of windmill-powered Archimedes' screws, were used during the Dutch Golden Age for land drainage as it could move large quantities of water in low heads.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Albert Koenig suggests that the screw was not widely used there as imperial scholars preferred works on philosophy, among other factors such as high production costs for an Archimedean screw and the impracticality of Virtuvius's design.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Portuguese traders ostensibly introduced the Archimedes' screw to Japan in 1637, with scrolls dating between the 1730s to the 1850s suggesting that miners in Sado used the Archimedes' screw for mining gold.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] In 1738, Daniel Bernoulli investigated the size of a pocket of water carried by a water screw; Leonhard Euler would later develop a question regarding the theory of the screw as part of his *Quaestiones Mathematicae*, 14 mathematical questions that were read to the Petersburg Academy in 1757.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] However, Archimedes' screws were not commonly used as water pumps when public water systems were first established in the early 19th century because of its low delivery head.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Dutch engineer Joan Muysken investigated the efficiency and discharge capacity of the Archimedes' screw in 1932, and developed the formula for the rotational speed of the screw.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] In 1991, Karl-August Radlik filed a patent for the Archimedes screw turbine (AST), in which mechanical power would be generated by pouring water from the top.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Academics note that the Archimedes' screw was proposed as a generator for mechanical power since 1862, with the screw being used to generate power since the early 1900s in places such as Japan.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Klaus Brada experimented with the Archimedes' screw as a turbine between 1993–1995 at the University of Prague, and found that most of the hydraulic energy collected by a screw can be converted to mechanical energy.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] An Archimedes' screw consists of a screw (a helical surface surrounding a central cylindrical shaft) inside a hollow pipe.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] The screw is usually turned by windmill, manual labour, cattle, or by modern means, such as a motor.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] As the shaft turns, the bottom end scoops up a volume of water.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] This water is then pushed up the tube by the rotating helicoid until it pours out from the top of the tube.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Helical blades are wrapped around a central tube, and attached to an enclosed cylinder, resulting in the entire structure to rotate.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Manufacturers do not often use casing tube, tube, and spiral screws as they have poor ventilation and often trap air.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] In an Archimedes' screw, there are several parameters to consider, mainly the external and internal parameters.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] The external parameters include the outer diameter of the screw ( $D_{O}$ ), the length of the screw ( L ), and the inclination angle of the screw ( $\beta$ ), whilst the internal parameters include the screw's inner radius ( $D_{i}$ ), the number of blades ( N ), and the screw's pitch ( S ).
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] The properties of the screw's installation site and passing volumetric flow rate often determine the external parameters.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] The contact surface between the screw and the pipe does not need to be perfectly watertight, as long as the amount of water being scooped with each turn is large compared to the amount of water leaking out of each section of the screw per turn.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] If water from one section leaks into the next lower one, it will be transferred upwards by the next segment of the screw.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] In some designs, the screw is fused to the casing and they both rotate together, instead of the screw turning within a stationary casing.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] The screw could be sealed to the casing with pitch resin or other adhesive, or the screw and casing could be cast together as a single piece in bronze.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Studies show that the volume of flow passing through Archimedes' screws is a function of inlet depth, diameter and rotation speed of the screw.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] The value of η could simply determinate using the $\eta$ graph or $\Theta$ graph.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] By determination of $D_{O}$ , other design parameters of Archimedes' screws can be calculated using a step-by-step analytical method.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Archimedes' screws transport liquids from one end to another.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] The screw was historically used as a water pump.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Screw turbines (ASTs) are a new form of generator for small hydroelectric powerplants that could be applied even in low-head sites.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] The low rotation speed of ASTs reduces negative effects on aquatic life.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] If water is fed into the top of an Archimedes' screw, it will force the screw to rotate.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] The rotating shaft can then be used to drive an electric generator.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Christian Rorres and Oleson posit that the Archimedes' screw's efficiency as a power generator, along with hydropower plants in Europe required to be fish-friendly, has encouraged its use.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Such an installation has the same benefits as using the screw for pumping: the ability to handle very dirty water and widely varying rates of flow at high efficiency.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Settle Hydro and Torrs Hydro are two reverse screw micro hydro schemes operating in England.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] The screw works well as a generator at low heads, commonly found in English rivers, including the Thames, powering Windsor Castle.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Archimedes' screws are used in sewage treatment plants because they cope well with varying rates of flow and with suspended solids.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] On a much larger scale, Archimedes's screws of decreasing pitch are used for the compaction of waste material.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] A variant of the Archimedes screw can also be found in some injection moulding machines, die casting machines and extrusion of plastics, which employ a screw of decreasing pitch to compress and melt the material.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] It is also used in a rotary-screw air compressor.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] A screw conveyor is a similar device which transports bulk materials such as powders and cereal grains.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] It is contained within a tube and turned by a motor to deliver material from one end of the conveyor to the other and particularly suitable for transport of granular materials.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] It may also be used to transport liquids.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] In industrial control applications, the conveyor may be used as a rotary feeder or variable rate feeder to deliver a measured rate or quantity of material into a process.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] This technology is used primarily at fish hatcheries to lift fish safely from ponds and transport them to another location.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] An Archimedes' screw was used in the successful 2001 stabilisation of the Leaning Tower of Pisa.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Small amounts of subsoil saturated by groundwater were removed from far below the north side of the tower, and the weight of the tower itself corrected the lean.
[src:archimedes-screw/archimedes-screw] Other inventions using Archimedes' screws include the auger conveyor in a snow blower, grain elevator, concrete mixer and chocolate fountain.
[src:archimedes-screw/asce-library] ASCE Journals first appeared online in the Fall of 2000.
[src:archimedes-screw/asce-library] The online collection was designated ASCE Research Library in the Fall of 2004 with the addition of ASCE Proceedings papers.
[src:archimedes-screw/asce-library] In June 2012, the platform migrated from Scitation, to Literatum managed by Atypon and the site was renamed ASCE Library.
[src:archimedes-screw/asce-library] In June 2013, e-books and standards were added with the ability to download individual book chapters as well as complete books.
[src:archimedes-screw/asce-library] In 2016, ASCE added access to premium content from Civil Engineering Magazine.
[src:archimedes-screw/asce-library] The ASCE Library offers online access to more than 150,000 technical and professional papers.
[src:archimedes-screw/asce-library] It encompasses the full text of papers published in 35 journals (as of 2019) from 1983 to the present, conference proceedings from 2000 to the present, and full text of ASCE standards and e-books.
[src:archimedes-screw/asce-library] The ASCE Library is supplemented by Civil Engineering Database (CEDB), a free bibliographic database offering records of all publications by American Society of Civil Engineers since 1872.
[src:archimedes-screw/asce-library] CEDB is updated at the end of each month.
[src:archimedes-screw/asce-library] The update includes the journal content for the following month and all other content published in the previous month.
[src:archimedes-screw/asce-library] Includes more than 750 proceedings titles and 70,000 technical papers, as well as a complete archive of conference proceedings papers from 2000 to present (selected earlier conference proceedings are also included).
